#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.svd:85
msgid ""
"SVD is usually described for the factorization of a 2D matrix :math:`A`. The "
"higher-dimensional case will be discussed below. In the 2D case, SVD is "
"written as :math:`A = U S V^H`, where :math:`A = a`, :math:`U= u`, :math:`S= "
"\\mathtt{np.diag}(s)` and :math:`V^H = vh`. The 1D array `s` contains the "
"singular values of `a` and `u` and `vh` are unitary. The rows of `vh` are "
"the eigenvectors of :math:`A^H A` and the columns of `u` are the "
"eigenvectors of :math:`A A^H`. In both cases the corresponding (possibly non-"
"zero) eigenvalues are given by ``s**2``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.svd:94
msgid ""
"If `a` has more than two dimensions, then broadcasting rules apply, as "
"explained in :ref:`routines.linalg-broadcasting`. This means that SVD is "
"working in \"stacked\" mode: it iterates over all indices of the first ``a."
"ndim - 2`` dimensions and for each combination SVD is applied to the last "
"two indices. The matrix `a` can be reconstructed from the decomposition with "
"either ``(u * s[..., None, :]) @ vh`` or ``u @ (s[..., None] * vh)``. (The "
"``@`` operator can be replaced by the function ``np.matmul`` for python "
"versions below 3.5.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.10/site-packages/numpy/linalg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of numpy.linalg.svd:103
msgid ""
"If `a` is a ``matrix`` object (as opposed to an ``ndarray``), then so are "
"all the return values."
msgstr ""

